<HL> Space Shuttle Has New Flaw; Test Is Aborted --- Valve Fails to Close Properly Or Is Misread by Sensor; Week's Delay Is Possible </HL>
<AUTHOR> Bob Davis (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> GOVMT </CO>
<IN> ARO </IN>
<DATELINE> CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla.  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ill-starred space shuttle program suffered yet another embarrassment.

   A moment before the space shuttle Discovery's three main engines were set to fire in a crucial test yesterday, an electronic engine controller automatically aborted the test.
The controller sensed that engine No. 2 -- a new engine that had never flown in space -- hadn't closed a critical valve fast enough and might leak pressurized fuel.
At worst, such a leak could rupture the engine.

   Scrubbing the test is the latest in a series of setbacks that have pushed the launching of Discovery far behind schedule.
This spring the National Aeronautics and Space Administration confidently predicted an August liftoff, and the agency still contends it can make it in September.
But now even October seems optimistic.
NASA has said it won't set a date until after it successfully completes the test firing.

   NASA first must figure out whether the shuttle engine actually malfunctioned or a sensor merely misread the situation.
The agency suspended the test until Sunday but said the delay could stretch until late next week depending on the severity of the problem.

   Boyce Mix, resident manager of NASA's Stennis Test Center in Bay St. Louis, Miss., where the engines are tested, said NASA hopes to decide today how to repair the problem.
The critical valve, an engine leak-valve, must be at least 80% closed before firing, NASA officials said, but in the test yesterday, according to the electronic controller, it had closed only 76%.

   Joseph Lombardo, project manager for the shuttle engines, said that NASA will remove the valve and sensor assembly if they are found faulty.
That would take about a week.
Alternatively, he said, NASA might decide to change the software controlling the valve.
That would take just a few days.

   Engine problems can sometimes lead to big delays.
During 1984, for instance, NASA delayed the maiden launch of Discovery for two months when it discovered an engine problem one second after the engines ignited.
NASA closed down the launch and later pulled the shuttle back to the assembly building, where workers replaced an engine.

   Neither of the changes contemplated by NASA would require the shuttle to be rolled off the launching pad.
But NASA faces additional delays because of a small fuel-line leak in a steering rocket.
NASA wants to repair the leak on the launching pad by cutting into the shuttle and clamping the leak.
But it hasn't attempted such a repair on the pad before.

   NASA had hoped to make yesterday's test firing a kind of confirmation party for the shuttle.
The space agency rolled the Discovery out of its hangar on July 4, a stirring sight that television news shows used as an optimistic counterpoint to stories about the U.S. Navy downing an Iranian passenger plane.
A successful test firing, which evaluates how spacecraft equipment performs under launch stress, would have demonstrated NASA's renewed technical prowess.

   About 50 reporters showed up to observe the 7:30 a.m. firing from a grandstand three miles from the launching pad.
NASA set up a souvenir stand nearby, and NASA workers watched the countdown from the roof of the flight control center, about a quarter-mile away.

   The countdown started flawlessly.
The escape walkway that astronauts use in case of disaster pulled back at seven minutes before ignition; the on-board computers switched on at 30 seconds before firing.
But then, at five seconds before launch, just when the main engines were to begin firing, the countdown shut down, the escape hatch jumped back into position, and NASA, once more, had to figure out what had gone wrong with the shuttle.

   No U.S. astronauts have been lofted since Jan. 28, 1986, when the shuttle Challenger exploded after liftoff and its seven crewmembers were killed.

</TEXT>
