<HEAD>Rocket Plant Contract Awarded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IUKA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockheed Missiles and Space Co. on Friday won
a $550 million contract to design and build a solid-rocket booster
plant in northeast Mississippi.
   Jerry Berg, a NASA spokesman at the Marshall Space Flight Center
in Huntsville, Ala., said the contract to Lockheed's Sunnyvale,
Calif., division includes $314 million to design and construct new
buildings or modify existing ones, and about $236 million to buy
equipment.
   The facilities will be constructed mainly at Yellow Creek near
Iuka, a government-owned site of an abandoned nuclear power plant.
Construction is expected to take 3{ years.
   NASA will also build a static motor test-firing stand at its
Stennis Space Center near Bay St. Louis, add nozzle production at
its Michoud Assembly Facility near New Orleans, and modify test
installations at the Marshall space center to accomodate the
advanced solid rocket motor, or ASRM.
   Lockheed Missile and Space Co. was awarded a $44 million
contract to build the test-firing stand at Stennis, NASA also
announced Friday.
   The ASRM is designed to replace the space shuttle's current
booster rockets in the mid-1990s.
   The contracts awarded Friday were companions to one awarded to
Lockheed May 11 covering design, development, test and evaluation
of the new rocket motor. Lon Miller, a spokesman at Stennis, said
construction would begin later this year or next, after necessary
permits are obtained.
   Rocket motor testing is scheduled to begin in 1993.
</TEXT>
