<NOTE>For Release Sun AMs Sept 18 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Engine Not Perfect, But Good Enough To Fly Shuttle Again,
Experts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When NASA engineers set out to develop a new
design for the space shuttle rocket boosters, they had to do it
fast, do it cheap and do it right.
   The result, say most experts, is a rocket that is just short of
the best design possible, but certainly good enough to get America
back into space and keep it there until better rockets are built.
   ``If you started with a clean sheet of paper, there are things
you could do'' to improve the rockets, said Russ Bardos, NASA's
director of shuttle propulsion. But he added: ``I'm perfectly
comfortable with what we have on there now.''
   Space shuttle Discovery stands poised to ride into space before
the end of the month on redesigned solid rocket boosters developed
in a crash program that lasted 31 months, required hundreds of
thousands of man hours and cost the nation $800 million.
   Better rocket engines will be built, said Bardos, but it will
take an additional four to five years and require even more money.
   The redesign program started after the Jan. 28, 1986, Challenger
explosion that bared serious problems with the boosters that 24
times previously had sent astronauts into orbit.
   Engineers deep in the structure of NASA had known as early as
1984 that leaking seals on the boosters threatened disaster. A
quiet program to develop a new booster design had been started at
the Marshall Space Flight Center and at Morton Thiokol, the Utah
manufacturer of the rocket.
   In the meantime, NASA expressed confidence in the boosters, and
withheld any concerns from the public and even from the astronauts.
The shuttles kept flying.
   A member of the Rogers Commission, which investigated the
Challenger accident, later described the decision to continue
flying as playing ``Russian roulette'' with a flawed and dangerous
system.
   The game ended when Challenger exploded and seven astronauts
died.
   A new team was named to correct the flawed boosters and some
members of the group later said they were amazed to find how little
data there was about about the internal workings of the rockets.
What appeared to be a simple steel tube filled with propellant was,
in fact, a complex machine.
   ``There was so much we didn't know,'' said Bardos. ``It needed a
lot of design work and changes.''
   The shuttle boosters are the largest solid-fueled rockets ever
made. Two are used to launch the shuttle and each is 149.16 feet
long and 12.17 feet in diameter. Loaded with 1.1 million pounds of
propellant, each boosters weighs 1.3 million pounds and produces
about 3.3 million pounds of thrust at launch, providing more than
two-thirds the lifting power to get the shuttle airborne.
   Because the boosters are so massive, they are manufactured in
four segments. Each of the steel casings are filled with a mixture
of chemicals that cure into a tough, rubber-like solid. The
segments are shipped to the Kennedy Space Center where they are
assembled.
   When the segments come together, they join at what is called a
field joint. It was a failed field joint that leaked and destroyed
Challenger.
   The field joints used for Challenger had a metal lip, called a
tang, that fit into a deep metal groove called a clevis. One side
of the clevis housed two O-rings, or rubberized seals. Bolts held
the clevis and tang together.
   When the propellant was ignited inside the rocket, a pressure of
up to 900 pounds per square inch and temperatures of several
thousand degrees immediately surged against the joint. The surge
was supposed to force the O-rings to seal the joint.
   However, engineers learned early in the shuttle program that the
sudden pressure actually caused the heavy steel casings to balloon
out, an action called ``rotation.'' This caused the joint to open
slightly. If the action was severe enough, the O-rings could lose
their capacity to seal.
   Low temperatures also affected the O-rings. When chilled, the
rubberized material became hard and sealed more slowly.
   When Challenger was launched, the boosters had been chilled by
sub-freezing temperatures overnight. Photos of the launch showed
that superheated gas escaped immediately from the lower field joint
on the right-hand booster. The rocket gases later melted through a
brace to free one end of the shuttle's massive fuel tank. The tank
ruptured and Challenger exploded just 73 seconds after launch.
</TEXT>
