<HL> Challenger Legacy: The Fear of Failure Frustrates Launching Of New Space Shuttle --- Efforts to Guarantee Safety May Create More Risks; NASA Loses Confidence --- This Time, No Schoolteachers </HL>
<AUTHOR> Bob Davis and Laurie McGinley (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> GOVMT MTI </CO>
<IN> ARO </IN>
<G> CNG </G>
<DATELINE> CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla.  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Will the U.S. muster the nerve to launch another space shuttle?

   No doubt it will, someday.
But for now, the terrible specter of Challenger stands in the way.

   Tormented by the 1986 disaster, second-guessed by congressmen and others, and overwhelmed by paper work, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's shuttle program advances warily.
NASA's efforts to guarantee a safe launch are complicating an already complex project.
The upshot: new and unpredictable risks.

   Says John Logsdon, director of the Space Policy Institute at George Washington University: "Somebody has to have the guts to say the damn thing is safe enough, and that it will never be 100% safe."

   The Discovery shuttle, already a year behind schedule, is supposed to be launched on Aug. 4.
But that will take "a miracle," says NASA administrator James Fletcher.
Another glitch, and the launch may get delayed until 1989, three years after the world watched an endearing young schoolteacher and six other all-American astronauts perish on live television.

   The memory is all too fresh here, and officials insist they'll never be rushed into another launch.
"We'll take whatever time it takes," snaps Forrest McCartney, the retired Air Force general who runs the Kennedy Space Center.
"We're not playing games here; we're talking about killing people.
Think I want to be part of an accident?
Not this boy."

   NASA is acutely aware the space program's future may ride on Discovery's success or failure.
Richard Truly, head of space flight at NASA, says another accident would deal a "fatal blow" to the shuttle.
Charles Redmond, a NASA spokesman who witnessed the Challenger explosion, says he and some other NASA managers won't travel to Florida to watch the next launch because of their "dread" of another crash.

   The next launch's crew will be strictly G.I. No women or civilians, and certainly no schoolteachers, will risk their lives in front of the nation's schoolchildren this time.
NASA, which once promised to send a journalist into space, now is considering keeping reporters 15 miles from the launch pad.
An explosion, the agency figures, could propel 100-pound chunks of metal into the press stands three miles away.

   Any one of a half-dozen NASA officials could have called off the Challenger countdown two years ago, but nobody spoke up.
The decision next time won't be made by default.
The final call will rest with one man, Robert Crippen, a dashing 50-year-old who piloted the first shuttle flight in 1981.
He can cancel the launch alone -- and he says he will certainly do so if any one of 20 key launch managers, in a last-minute poll, raises an objection.

   Mr. Crippen, whose 1981 flight prompted tens of thousands of letters from admiring female fans, keeps a figure of a rocket-riding Superman -- with Mr. Crippen's face -- in his office.
Mr. Crippen vows he won't be intimidated by senior NASA officials.
"If they don't like my decision," he says with cocky self-confidence, "they can fire me."

   But Superman never worked for a NASA.
The agency's management style discourages decisive action and encourages delays.
The launch is still a long way off.
Minor technical glitches have brought work on the shuttle to a halt at times.
Endless meetings have preoccupied managers and eroded their self-confidence.
Until the launch date, says James Beggs, a former NASA administrator, "There are too many people who can say no."

   Some old NASA hands say the caution could backfire, and compromise the mission's safety.
If "jumpy" officials allow a series of delays, says Alex Roland, a former NASA historian who now teaches at Duke University, "then they'll be in the same fix as they were before Challenger; they'll feel under public pressure to launch."

   Challenger exploded on Jan. 28, 1986, when hot gases escaped from a tiny gap in a rocket-motor seal.
On a warmer day with milder winds, the seal might well have held.
NASA later rejected advice that it simply patch the seals and launch only on a warm day to eliminate the risk.
It chose to redesign the entire system.

   The cautious approach has created new problems, as when workers found they couldn't tighten some bolts on Discovery's solid rocket boosters exactly the way instruction manuals dictated.
Before they tried again, Mr. McCartney says, he insisted the California engineer who wrote the instructions rewrite them.
In other cases, decisions have been bucked upward.
For example, the shuttle director in Washington, D.C., must give his approval before workers in Florida can use parts from reserve shuttles on Discovery.

   Astronauts had little management responsibility before.
Now they play a major role in management.
"Everybody thinks test pilots are brave," says Mr. Truly, himself a former test pilot and astronaut, "but really they are the most conservative people I know.
The way to become a successful test pilot is to stack up as many of the odds you can in your favor, and then fly.
Space flight is like that, 10 times over."

   While Mr. Crippen's decision will determine whether Discovery lifts off or remains earthbound, he shares with Mr. Truly control of the launch date.
A rear admiral who piloted the second space shuttle mission, Mr. Truly heads review sessions at which NASA employees and contractors swear that subsystems are in working order.
A few weeks before the launch, Mr. Truly will preside over a final review.

   Then Mr. Crippen, a midlevel manager, takes over.
He will start the countdown 55 hours before launch, order the final Go nine minutes before blastoff -- and, if any last-minute glitches go unrepaired, cancel it.
Afterward, he will jet to the Johnson Space Center in Houston to track the shuttle's flight.

   Mr. Crippen blames himself for not asking more probing questions of shuttle engineers before the Challenger disaster.
Now he says he's pressing them to ensure that Discovery is safe.
But many other people take part in decision-making before launch.
And NASA, sensitive to complaints that it ignored critics before the Challenger accident, will listen to nearly anybody now.
Its safety work and redesign are reviewed by two National Academy of Sciences panels and by other panels in NASA and Congress.

   On launch day, Mr. Crippen will huddle with a team of 20 NASA managers and contractors in a glass-enclosed corner of the launch room, while most of his bosses will peer over his shoulder from another glass enclosure across the room.
They are linked by intercom and telephone.

   Mr. Crippen says he will poll the members of his team at nine minutes before launch to make sure every one of them agrees to proceed.
He requires unanimity.
"I can't foresee circumstances where if someone is uncomfortable about launching on my team, I'll override them," he says.

   At least one of Mr. Crippen's bosses across the launch room, George Rodney, NASA's chief of safety, says he wants to vote on the launch, too.
"I'll have no compunction telling Bob Crippen there's something wrong and he'll have to react to it," Mr. Rodney says.

   For all its prudence, NASA is still capable of boners.
In March 1987 -- more than a year after Challenger -- a NASA team launched an unmanned Atlas Centaur rocket into a thunderstorm and watched, awestruck, as a bolt of lightning destroyed it.
The agency now says it won't launch Discovery if there is a cloud nearby.

   NASA also says it won't launch if the temperature is below 39 degrees, even though it added heaters to make such launches safe.
To make triply sure nothing goes awry, it will refrigerate a solid rocket booster for 30 days and test-fire it if the launch is scheduled for an autumn, and probably cool, day.

   The harsh truth is that none of this guarantees a safe launch.
The agency says it has spent $800 million and made about 400 changes in the orbiter, two solid rocket boosters and giant fuel tank that constitute the shuttle.
But it remains an astonishingly fragile machine.
Should any of nearly 5,000 critical components fail during flight, NASA calculates, the shuttle could crash.
Should one solid rocket booster fire just a moment before the other, the shuttle would topple in an enormous explosion.

   Besides this, says Charles Perrow, a Yale University sociologist who studies complex mechanical systems, improvements to machines often create new and unexpected faults.
"The safety devices themselves become more and more the source of accidents," he says.

   On the shuttle's solid rocket boosters, for instance, NASA engineers worried that a gap could open in the joint connecting a nozzle to the bottom of the rocket, leaking hot gases.
So they tightened the joint by adding 100 bolts.
But Roger Boisjoly, a former engineer for rocket-maker Morton Thiokol Inc. who warned NASA against launching the Challenger, thinks the redesign may make the Discovery less safe.
Now there are 100 more places to spring a leak.
Says Mr. Boisjoly: "NASA violated the cardinal rule in mechanical design: Keep it simple, stupid."

   NASA says it has confidence in its joint design.
It is being rigorously tested along with the rest of the shuttle system.
The agency plans to fire two more solid rocket boosters at Morton Thiokol's Wasatch, Utah, test range, and then spend two weeks dissecting the rockets to see how their parts performed.
NASA also will fire Discovery's liquid-propellant engines at Kennedy before launch.

   But the tests can't predict whether Discovery's rocket boosters will work as well as the test rockets.
Each booster is essentially made by hand and differs a trifle from others.
Those of the Challenger era worked well enough in tests and on 24 flights, only to fail catastrophically on the 25th.
"The ultimate test is the launch," says David Winterhalter, NASA's director of systems engineering and design.

   Before testing, NASA predicts how parts will fare.
Afterward it compares its predictions with results.
This post-Challenger procedure detects flaws but also can create new problems.
In a test last December, a rocket-motor part unexpectedly burned off in testing.
Had this occurred in flight, it wouldn't have endangered the shuttle.
Nonetheless, NASA replaced the part with one made from a backup design, delaying the launch another two months more.

   Another delay is likely.
The prospect dismays Rep. Robert Torricelli, a New Jersey Democrat who sits on a House panel overseeing NASA.
Once he had criticized NASA for ignoring safety.
Now he says he's more worried about "NASA's failure of nerve."

   Mr. Truly shrugs it off.
"How do I balance being called a wimp on the one hand and unsafe on the other?" he asks.

</TEXT>
