<HEAD>NASA Reschedules Test of Shuttle Engines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with NASA rescheduling hot-fire test,
other details; ADDS byline. No Pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA today rescheduled the crucial
hot-fire test of shuttle Discovery's engines for Wednesday morning
after replacing the defective valve-sensor combination that caused
a last-second scrub last week.
   The test, in which all three of the shuttle's engines are fired,
was set for 7:30 a.m. EDT. Technicians will begin the countdown for
the test at 6:10 p.m. Tuesday.
   The shuttle's engines were to have been tested last Thursday,
but the sensor reported that a one-inch valve which circulates
coolant before firing had not closed to where it was supposed to
be. The engines' onboard computer, sensing a malfunction, aborted
the test before ignition.
   Technicians spent the weekend swapping out the mechanism. Today,
the blast doors that protect the shuttle during the firing were
being installed and scaffolding removed.
   The engines will be fired for 22 seconds with the shuttle bolted
firmly to the pad. The ship's two solid fuel booster rockets will
not be ignited.
   The firing tests not only the engines, but the entire countdown
process, the shuttle system and launch teams. It is a requirement
since no shuttle has flown in the more than 2{ years since the
Challenger explosion. Dicovery is being treated as if it were an
untried new ship.
   No date has been set for Discovery's launch with five astronauts
on board, but five postponements of the hot-fire test to date have
made it all but certain that NASA can't meet a late September
target.
   The sensor, which signals the valve's open-closed position to
the ship's onboard computer, gave a wrong reading last Thursday,
and the flight readiness firing test was aborted. Engineers
determined that the valve was in the proper position but decided to
replace both because they are in the same subassembly.
   That work was finished by midnight Saturday; crews spent Sunday
reconnecting lines and hoses and testing everything for leaks.
</TEXT>
