<HEAD>Morton Thiokol, NASA Conduct Next-To-Last Shuttle Test</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to update with officials' comments on
test, picking up at the 10th graf previous, `The booster...'; Also
moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morton Thiokol Inc. test-fired its
redesigned solid fuel booster rocket Tuesday with no apparent
problems in the second-to-last test before shuttle flights are to
resume.
   ``All indications are we had an excellent test,'' said Royce
Mitchell, solid rocket program manager for the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration. ``Everything went smoothly. The motor
performed very, very well.''
   Brilliant yellow flame erupted from the 126-foot-long rocket and
grayish-brown smoke billowed thousands of feet into the air amid a
roar that could be heard for miles.
   The 122-second horizontal test, conducted at 1 p.m. MDT at
Morton Thiokol's Wasatch Operations plant west of here, was the
fourth of five tests required to qualify major design features of
the solid fuel booster before the shuttle program, grounded after
the 1986 Challenger disaster, can resume.
   ``We've got a lot of work to do,'' said J.R. Thompson, director
of the Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Ala. ``Barring
some surprise, I feel very good about'' an August launch.
   Allen McDonald, Morton Thiokol vice president of engineering,
said preliminary data indicated that the motor successfully
withstood the simulated liftoff and flight stresses.
   ``From all aspects, we can say it was a totally successful
test,'' McDonald said. ``I hope it looks as good from the inside as
it does on the outside.''
   ``It's an extremely good test,'' Mitchell said.
   He said engineers will spend the next two days studying computer
readouts of the test and disassembling the motor, and officials
expect to have a complete analysis within two weeks.
   Fifteen minutes after the test, a nozzle exit cone toppled from
the rear of the motor to simulate its separation from the motor
during a flight.
   NASA has scheduled an Aug. 31 launch of the shuttle Discovery.
   The booster tested Tuesday was free of planned flaws introduced
in previous tests to determine whether the joint can withstand the
intense heat and pressures of launch even in the event of some
failures, Morton Thiokol spokesman Rocky Raab said.
   It also was the first use of a new $22 million test stand, which
has 1,216 channels of instrumentation and uses hydraulic struts to
duplicate steering, flight turbulence and other stresses the motor
will endure during launch, he said.
   The building also can heat an entire motor to 110 degrees
Fahrenheit or cool it to 20 degrees. The rocket's 1.1 million
pounds of propellant has been heated to a uniform 90 degrees, or
about 20 degrees warmer than the usual launch temperature, to allow
engineers to test its performance at the upper limit for an actual
launch, Raab said.
   David Ewing, deputy director of program management for Morton
Thiokol, said the hydraulic struts that duplicate launch stresses
are based on ``the worst-case sideloads'' experienced in past
shuttle flights.
   During launch the boosters flex about 26 inches at the tip,
creating a ``twang,'' he said. The test simulated those pressures
on the rocket motor's joints.
   The Challenger explosion on Jan. 28, 1986, was blamed on a
faulty booster joint that allowed a plume of superhot gas to snake
through an O-ring, triggering the blast that killed the seven crew
members.
   The new joint incorporates three Viton O-rings instead of two, a
metal lip to help hold the joint together and an adhesively bonded
relief slot that reduces stresses and increases the sealing action
of the bonded surface under pressure, Raab said.
   Moreover, the rocket's three field joints are equipped with
heaters to maintain a minimum temperature of 75 degrees Fahrenheit.
Sub-freezing temperatures the night before the doomed Challenger
launch were found to have contributed to the failure of the joint.
   For the experiment simulating the nozzle exit cone's separation
during flight, the test device was fitted with an explosive
severance system activated 15 minutes after the test.
   Dozens of visitors from Chicago-based Morton Thiokol, NASA and
various subcontractors were at the remote desert plant to watch
Tuesday's test.
   The final full-scale test is scheduled for some time in July. At
that time, severe flaws will be introduced in the joints ``to test
the system to its limits,'' Raab said.
   Testing of the redesigned motor has gone so well, he said, that
Discovery's two boosters were hooked up Friday with an external
fuel tank at Cape Canaveral, Fla., and the stack was to be joined
with the shuttle Thursday.
