<HEAD>Space Shuttle Discovery Connected To Its Booster Rockets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Space shuttle Discovery was linked
Friday to the two solid fuel booster rockets that are to hurl it
into space this summer on the first post-Challenger shuttle mission.
   A giant overhead crane hoisted the 85-ton spaceship on a metal
sling and gingerly guided it into position for mating with the
126-foot-tall boosters and a 154-foot fuel tank that will feed the
craft's three liquid fuel engines.
   NASA workers then made electrical, fuel line and other
connections. On Sunday, they will begin testing the connections.
   Barring problems, Discovery will be transported to the launch
pad in the glare of powerful floodlights Friday, starting at 12:01
a.m. The ship's five-man astronaut crew and NASA officials will
participate in the rollout ceremony from a flag-bedecked grandstand
outside the shuttle assembly building.
   Forrest McCartney, director of the Kennedy Space Center, will
present the astronauts with an autograph book which they will carry
into space on their four-day mission. The book contains the
signatures of the 15,000 center workers here who have labored to
return the shuttle fleet to space.
   McCartney has invited center workers and their families to drive
their personal cars onto the spaceport that day for a drive around
the launch pad to view Discovery there.
   Discovery's linkup with the boosters was delayed more than a day
while engineers overcame a problem with a mechanism controlling the
landing wheel doors in Discovery's nose.
   The shuttle was moved into the assembly building Tuesday after
undergoing an extensive overhaul of several of its systems, many of
the changes the result of the Challenger explosion that killed
seven astronauts shortly after liftoff on Jan. 28, 1986.
   The disaster was blamed on a faulty joint in one of Challenger's
solid fuel boosters. The joint has been redesigned and has passed
four test-firings, with one more set for July 26 before Discovery
is cleared for flight.
   The three main engines also must undergo a pre-flight test. That
20-second firing, with Discovery bolted on the pad, is set for July
22.
   The current launch target date is Sept. 3 but officials say
there is a chance liftoff could occur in late August.
   During the flight, commander Rick Hauck and his crew will deploy
a communications satelite, conduct science and technology
experimets and test modifications made to the shuttle. The other
crew members are Dick Covey, Mike Lounge, George Nelson and David
Hilmers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

