<HEAD>Engineer Says NASA Not Reluctant To Fly Space Shuttle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA is taking a slow, cautious
approach in returning space shuttles to flight, but a leading
shuttle engineer says that doesn't mean anyone at the agency is
afraid to fly.
   ``I don't see anybody in the decision-making process who is
reticent about pressing on and let's get back in the air. ...
Personally, I have no hestitancy about returning to flight,'' John
Thomas said Monday.
   Thomas is manager of the team that has redesigned and is testing
the solid fuel booster rocket that caused the shuttle Challenger
explosion 26 months ago. The accident killed the seven crew
members, and the remainder of the fleet has been grounded while
NASA tests the redesigned booster joint.
   Workers here have begun assembling the first of the two booster
rockets intended to propel the shuttle Discovery into space when
flights resume. NASA has set a launch date of Aug. 4.
   ``We've been very careful with our design and test programs and
we've been very cautious in the assembly process,'' Thomas said at
a news conference at the Marshall Space Flight Center, in
Huntsville, Ala., which was monitored by reporters here.
   Thomas said the redesign test program has gone so well that the
stacking of the rocket segments could proceed with confidence even
though three critical test firings remain for the overhauled model
of the rocket.
   ``We're well on our way in the test program,'' he said.
``Everything is going well with the processing at the Kennedy Space
Center.''
   On May 1, the two boosters are to be mated with the huge
external fuel tank, and on May 14, Discovery will be attached to
the stack. Rollout to the launch pad is set for May 24, and a
20-second on-the-pad firing of the shuttle's three main engines is
scheduled for June 15, leading to the Aug. 4 launch with a crew of
five.
   Thomas said three more full-scale tests of the redesigned
booster must be accomplished successfully before Discovery can fly.
They are scheduled for April 20, June 3 and mid-July at the Brigham
City, Utah, facility of the manufacturer, Morton Thiokol.
   Asked if there was anything that could delay the August launch
date, Thomas said, ``We have a very ambitious processing flow down
at the Cape, and we could always stub our toe someplace along the
way ... or have something unusual turn up in the test program.
   ``But I don't see anything now that would prevent an August
launch.''
</TEXT>
