<TEXT>

   1988

   Jan. 27: NASA sets Aug. 4 for resumption of shuttle flights.
   Feb. 11: The Reagan administration issues new space policy with
a greatly enhanced role for private industry. The policy affirms
NASA's goal to build a space station.
   April 26: Aldrich cites unexpected delays, says shuttle launch
won't be before Aug. 14.
   May 4: Explosions level the plant of Pacific Engineering in
Henderson, Nev., one of two U.S. makers of ammonium perchlorate, a
key component in the shuttle boosters. With only four flight sets
of boosters on hand, NASA worries whether there will be enough fuel
to meet 1989 flight schedule.
   June 10: NASA says Aug. 31 launch target possible.
   June 14: The redesigned booster passes the fourth of its five
full-scale test firings.
   June 21: The 600-day overhaul of Discovery is complete and the
shuttle is ready to be mated with its fuel tank and boosters.
   June 28: NASA concedes it can't meet August launch target; aims
for early September.
   July 4: Discovery is moved to the launch pad.
   July 15: Small gas leak found in one of Discovery's steering
engines; NASA sees possibility of additional delay in launch, now
set for Sept. 3.
   July 22: Launch-pad test firing of shuttle delayed two days, to
July 30, after officials decide not all elements are ready.
   July 29: Test delayed a third time in week by leak in hydrogen
line during fueling; set for Aug. 4.
   Aug. 1: Another hydrogen leak is detected but NASA goes ahead
with a countdown rehearsal.
   Aug. 4: Test firing is aborted when a computer reports a valve
not closed and shuts down engines a fraction of a second before
they were to ignite. Valve is replaced in succeeding days.
   Aug. 10: Discovery's main engines fire flawlessly.
   Aug. 18: A shuttle booster, deliberately flawed, undergoes the
fifth and final full-scale firing and use of the new design is
approved for flight.
   Aug. 19: Leak in steering engine sealed by a clamshell device
after workers cut access hole through cargo bay wall.
   Aug. 29: A $100 million Tracking and Data Relay satellite, the
main cargo for the first post-Challenger flight, is loaded into
Discovery. NASA officials decide not to announce a launch date
until after a flight readiness review on Sept. 13-14.
   Aug. 30: NASA revamps its schedule and postpones the June 1,
1989, launch of the $1.5 billion Hubble Space Telescope from the
shuttle until Feb. 1, 1990.
   Sept. 2: A Titan 34D rocket launches a spy satellite from Cape
Canaveral, but its apogee stage fails to fire and it is put into a
useless orbit.
   Sept. 9: Discovery crew finishes two days of countdown rehearsal
in the shuttle, proclaim themselves ready to fly.
   Sept. 13: National Research Council panel finds ``no basis for
objection to the current launch schedule for STS-26.''
</TEXT>
