<HEAD>Coping With NASA Jargon ``Like Being Able to Order Your Meals in
French''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Those uneducated in the art of
NASAspeak might think LOX is eaten with bagels, a POD is home to a
pea, SMU is a college in Texas and MUM describes a pantomimist.
   Many of the journalists covering the flight of space shuttle
Discovery were new to the space agency's jargon and quickly became
frustrated trying to translate the language of the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   For its part, NASA hummed along SOP.
   ``When we bring someone in to brief reporters, they speak in
their normal tongue. It becomes a quick way of communicating,''
said Pat Phillips, a NASA spokeswoman.
   ``At the end of their first mission, they (reporters) are pretty
conversant. It's like (at the end of a trip to Paris) being able to
order your meals in French and navigate around the city,'' she said.
   Phillips said there are about 20 to 30 ``major'' acronyms and
that ``once you learn these you are truly conversant.''
   Frequently at the shuttle briefings, NASA officials referred to
GSE, for ground support equipment, IMF, or in-flight maintenance,
TAL, trans-Atlantic abort landing sites, and TDRS, pronounced
tee-drus and standing for Tracking and Data Relay Satellite, the
$100 million communications satellite that was deployed on
Discovery's first day in orbit.
   NASA included a 4{-page glossary of acronyms in its press kit
for the Discovery flight, which drew 2,318 news media
representatives to the Kennedy Space Center to cover the first
shuttle launch since the Challenger disaster Jan. 28, 1986.
   The acronyms in the press kit were culled from a 138-page
terminology guide given to space center employees. NASA
headquarters in Washington has a 305-page guide, with about 15
terms per page.
   At one pre-launch briefing, a frustrated reporter suggested
another acronym for the space agency's lexicon: AFE, meaning
acronyms for everything.
   Other reporters, including longtime space writers, applauded his
request that NASA briefers speak English.
   ``It's a problem,'' said Ron Kotulak, a Chicago Tribune reporter
who has covered space launches for more than 20 years. ``It's like
the priesthood using symbols to keep the outside out.''
   Hugh J. Martin, covering his first shuttle launch for the Tampa
Tribune, said some reporters were confused by NASA's explanation of
a damaged O-ring on a rocket being prepared for a future shuttle
flight.
   ``A large number of people didn't understand most of that
(explanation), but what they did understand was that there was a
cut in an O-ring,'' he said.
   It was a flawed O-ring joining segments of a booster rocket that
allowed superheated gas to burn through and spark the explosion
that destroyed Challenger.
   Martin said some newspapers reported the story incorrectly,
making the problem seem more critical than it actually was.
   ``In that case, NASA shot themselves in the foot,'' he said.
   Frank Merlino, NASA test director, said the jargon ``really
helps to condense conversations to the action. It's like slang. It
lets you get your point across quickly.''
   FYI, LOX stands for liquid oxygen, POD is the payload operations
director, SMU means speaker-microphone unit, and MUM is the mass
memory unit manager.
</TEXT>
