<HEAD>NASA Selects Mississippi Sites For New Rocket Engine Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA has selected two sites in Mississippi as
the best locations for proposed government-owned facilities for the
production and testing of a new space shuttle solid rocket motor,
the space agency announced today.
   A location in northeastern Mississippi known as Yellow Creek was
selected as a production site for the space shuttle advanced solid
rocket motor, NASA said, and the Stennis Space Center near Bay St.
Louis, Miss., has been selected as a site for the testing of the
motor.
   Yellow Creek is owned by the Tennessee Valley Authority, and
Stennis is a NASA facility.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration said work at
the Yellow Creek site could provide about 1,400 new jobs, and an
additional 600 jobs would be created at Bay St. Louis.
   The space shuttle advanced solid rocket motor is planned to
replace the current redesigned shuttle rocket motor in the
mid-1990s. The advanced motor is expected to provide more
reliability and safety, and enable the space shuttle to carry more
cargo into orbit.
   Under the NASA advanced rocket motor plan, the space agency will
now ask for contract proposals for work on the rocket motor at the
two Mississippi sites. Companies will be asked to make bids on
building a government-owned facility that would be operated by the
contractor.
   Companies may also propose that the work be done in facilities
built and owned by contractors at a privately owned site of the
contractor's choosing.
   After evaluating the options, NASA will make a final decision on
the advanced solid rocket motor contract.
   NASA said that an advanced solid rocket motor program in
Mississippi will make ``maximum utilization'' of the Michoud
Assembly Facility and the Slidell Computer Complex, both located
nearby in southeastern Louisiana.
</TEXT>
